Strong priorities for fragile states.
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared from the fallout of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states are facing a particularly complex set of issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and a deficient public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to navigate the pandemic is precisely what fragile states are lacking: a functional state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, and healthcare services to treat infected individuals.
The lack of state resources is immediately felt in the area of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also relies on trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states hardly enjoys the consent of the population.
In countries recovering from conflict or plagued by endemic corruption, several people will be reluctant to back the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and resilient states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would escape the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the young and geographical distance.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, it is clear that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all seen infection and mortality rates comparable to those of developed countries that were initially hit by the coronavirus.
The economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These will not only result from national lockdowns, but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has faltered, remittances from expatriates have plummeted, the prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
Since fragile states rely heavily on imports for most of their food, there is increasingly talk of "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now understand that the problems of less affluent countries have become largely global issues, whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the disadvantaged populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only worsen.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must face.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business leaders, academics, as well as presidents of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its purpose will be to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will navigate this crisis and address their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the wise use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that targeted lockdowns of local outbreaks are often more suitable than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act swiftly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
At times, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be leveraged to collect information on immediate needs and disburse regular, albeit limited, small stipends.
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which was previously a rice producer, has become increasingly dependent over the last few decades.
In general, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Basic crop production initiatives must be rapidly deployed on a much broader scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states' businesses need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small businesses in less affluent countries are often overlooked and suffer the detrimental consequences of broader objectives and rules (since it is easier to achieve an objective by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
It is precisely these small businesses that require more substantial investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is anticipated that countries receiving bilateral development aid will repay around $40 billion to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend, for a time, not only the accumulated debts until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
In addition, it is crucial that all fragile states receive emergency funding to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic impacts — particularly countries that do not normally have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
The COVID-19 pandemic will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts quickly, we can mitigate the worst impacts of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it's that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
